<subSubSection lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1017,1992]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1260,1286]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[352,456,1260,1286]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete, with eight thoracic and 40 abdominal chaetigers. Body length 
<quantity box="[1277,1365,1260,1287]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
, branchial crown 
<quantity box="[292,381,1294,1321]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
, maximum body width 
<quantity box="[652,756,1295,1321]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="0.26">0.26 mm</quantity>
. Natural brown colouration present especially in the thorax, highlighting the mid-dorsally faecal groove, and ventral shields (
<figureCitation box="[892,999,1329,1355]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1459,1483]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,187,1426]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1436,181,1435]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 20. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636188/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
). Crown holding five pairs of radioles with 15 pairs of long pinnules in two symmetrical not alternating rows. Gap between pairs decreasing along the radiole from the base to the distal end, with the first two basal pairs more separated from the others. Pinnules of similar length (1/4 of the total radiolar length) and with the last two distal pairs and the first two basal pairs slightly shorter. Radiolar bare tips long1/3 of the total radiolar length, with a blunt end (
<figureCitation box="[951,1054,1468,1494]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1459,1483]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,187,1426]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1436,181,1435]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 20. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636188/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
). Radiolar skeleton with two rows of cells. Dorsal lips almost identical in length to pinnules, being 1/4 of the total radiolar length. Anterior peristomial ring visible, high and with similar height all around. Anterior peristomial ring low. Both peristomial rings appeared connected to highly developed ventral basal flanges, which extend as prominent ridges from base of ventralmost radioles (
<figureCitation box="[255,391,1607,1633]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1459,1483]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,187,1426]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1436,181,1435]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 20. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636188/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 20D, E</figureCitation>
). Peristomial eyes not visible. Pygidial eyes present as brown cluster spots on lateral margins of pygidium. Thorax longer than wide. First thoracic chaetiger bearing only 3 chaetae similar in shape to the superior thoracic ones. Second to eighth thoracic chaetigers with 4 uncini per torus, having well-developed breast, large space to main fang, approximately four rows of long teeth above main fang, and a medium handle (0.40) (
<figureCitation box="[1320,1424,1713,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,534,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[151,1436,525,1848]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 21. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636190/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 21A</figureCitation>
). Companion chaetae with straight shaft and long mucro (
<figureCitation box="[772,873,1749,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,534,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[151,1436,525,1848]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 21. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636190/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 21B</figureCitation>
). Second to eighth thoracic chaetigers with 4 chaetae, of which one is a superior broadly hooded chaeta (
<figureCitation box="[766,869,1785,1811]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,534,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[151,1436,525,1848]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 21. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636190/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 21D</figureCitation>
), and three paleate chaetae in inferior row on each thoracic chaetiger, with long mucro (longer than the hood) (
<figureCitation box="[823,925,1821,1847]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,534,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[151,1436,525,1848]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 21. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636190/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 21E</figureCitation>
). Four abdominal uncini on each torus higher than longer and with similar-sized small teeth above the main fang, with a medium handle, and also in this species with a large height as observed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[540,717,1893,1920]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="vulcanoensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[540,717,1893,1920]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">A. vulcanoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[725,815,1893,1919]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[725,815,1893,1919]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[872,1016,1893,1920]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aeoliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[872,1016,1893,1920]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">A. aeoliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1023,1114,1893,1919]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1023,1114,1893,1919]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, (
<figureCitation box="[1137,1241,1893,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,534,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[151,1436,525,1848]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 21. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636190/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 21C</figureCitation>
). Two abdominal broadly hooded neurochaetae similar to the thoracic paleate in the first abdominal chaetigers, becoming more geniculate in the middle segments (
<figureCitation box="[521,655,1965,1992]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,534,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[151,1436,525,1848]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 21. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636190/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 21G, F</figureCitation>
). Spermathechae light brown/red coloured, not conspicuous.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636188" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4636188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636188/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" startId="27.[151,250,1459,1483]" targetBox="[161,1428,187,1426]" targetPageId="27">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1459,1519]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1459,1483]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">FIGURE 20.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[294,543,1459,1483]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="panareensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[294,543,1459,1483]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">Amphiglena panareensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[550,654,1459,1483]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[550,631,1459,1483]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
A
</emphasis>
. entire worm, photo from the holotype; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1061,1084,1459,1483]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">B.</emphasis>
staining pattern; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1260,1285,1459,1483]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">C.</emphasis>
tip of the radiole; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,220,1495,1519]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">D.</emphasis>
photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[998,1021,1495,1519]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">E.</emphasis>
scheme of the anterior end ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1565,2024]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,401,1565,1591]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">Staining pattern.</emphasis>
In both thorax and abdomen stain only ventral shields, showing a square shape in the thorax and a longer double thin rectangular shape in the abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[822,925,1601,1627]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1459,1483]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,187,1426]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1436,181,1435]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 20. Amphiglena panareensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636188/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">Fig. 20B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1565,2024]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1637,1663]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">Variation.</emphasis>
Individuals always with 8 thoracic chaetigers and up to 42 abdominal chaetigers. Mean body length of 
<quantity box="[181,246,1673,1700]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
and mean crown length of 
<quantity box="[550,638,1673,1700]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
. Peristomial eyes visible in some specimens. Up to 6 thoracic uncini on each torus and 6 thoracic uncini one on each torus (
<tableCitation box="[726,810,1709,1735]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="29.[151,239,689,715]" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparative view of the main characters of the described Amphiglena species." pageId="27" pageNumber="228">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="229" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1565,2024]" lastBlockId="28.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="229" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1745,1771]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">Remarks</emphasis>
. The main feature distinguishes this new taxon is its elongate appearance, that also includes the base of the crown. Moreover, members of this species have the highest and more developed ventral basal flanges, extending as prominent ridges, observed in the genus. The elongate base of the crown appears similar to a web and in some specimens makes difficult to see the base of the peristomial ring. This is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[1198,1330,1854,1880]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="gravinae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1198,1330,1854,1880]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">A. gravinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1338,1429,1853,1879]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1338,1429,1853,1879]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, described from the Adriatic Sea, from which it is distinguished especially for the different development of both the peristomial rings, but also for the length of handle of abdominal uncini, for the highest number of thoracic paleate chaetae, and for the shape of abdominal chaetae. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[831,997,1962,1988]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="panareensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[831,997,1962,1988]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">A. panareensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1005,1095,1961,1987]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1005,1095,1961,1987]" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is longer than 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[1264,1396,1962,1988]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="27" pageNumber="228" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="gravinae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1264,1396,1962,1988]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">A. gravinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="27" pageNumber="228" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
In addition, this is the second Mediterranean taxon showing pinnules arranged in pairs not alternating along the radiole. Among the non Mediterranean taxa, high developed ventral flanges are present also in 
<taxonomicName authority="Capa &amp; Rouse, 2007" authorityName="Capa &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2007" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bondi">
<emphasis box="[1274,1371,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">A. bondi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Capa, M. &amp; Rouse, G. W." pageId="28" pageNumber="229" pagination="327 - 356" refId="ref18604" refString="Capa, M. &amp; Rouse, G. W. (2007) Phylogenetic relationships within Amphiglena Claparede, 1864 (Polychaeta: Sabellidae), description of five new species from Australia, a new species from Japan, and comments on previously described species. Journal of Natural History, 41, 327 - 356. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930701194938" type="journal article" year="2007">Capa &amp; Rouse, 2007</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, however, this is a thin and more compact species, with a longer branchial crown bearing 6 radioles with similar length. Lastly, the brown colouration appears clearer and more homogeneous than that observed in specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[305,448,259,285]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aeoliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[305,448,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">A. aeoliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[455,546,259,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[455,540,259,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
described in the present paper from the same area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="229" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,295,321]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named from 
<typeStatus box="[665,713,295,321]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">type</typeStatus>
locality, the island of Panarea (Aeolian Archipelago) (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Auriemma, R. &amp; De Vittor, C. &amp; Esposito, V. &amp; Gaglioti, M. &amp; Gambi, M. C." pageId="28" pageNumber="229" pagination="216 - 219" refId="ref17998" refString="Auriemma, R., De Vittor, C., Esposito, V., Gaglioti, M. &amp; Gambi, M. C. (2019) Motile Fauna associated to Cystoseira brachycarpa along a gradient of Ocean Acidification at a vent system off Panarea (Aeolian Islands, Italy). Biologia Marina Mediterranea, 26 (1), 216 - 219." type="journal article" year="2019">
Auriemma 
<emphasis box="[244,300,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
for a description of the collection area).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="229" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,505,366,393]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">Distribution and Ecology.</emphasis>
This species represents, together with 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[939,1082,367,393]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aeoliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[939,1082,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">A. aeoliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1089,1178,367,393]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1089,1178,367,393]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, one of the most abundant taxa of the benthic community associated to the macroalga 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Agardh" authorityYear="1896" box="[871,1141,403,429]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Cystoseiraceae" genus="Cystoseira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fucales" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Phaeophyta" rank="species" species="brachycarpa">
<emphasis box="[871,1141,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">Cystoseira brachycarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the brown habitat-former alga dominating the rocks of the Bottaro crater and the hydrothermal system around it (
<bibRefCitation author="Auriemma, R. &amp; De Vittor, C. &amp; Esposito, V. &amp; Gaglioti, M. &amp; Gambi, M. C." box="[1135,1389,439,465]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" pagination="216 - 219" refId="ref17998" refString="Auriemma, R., De Vittor, C., Esposito, V., Gaglioti, M. &amp; Gambi, M. C. (2019) Motile Fauna associated to Cystoseira brachycarpa along a gradient of Ocean Acidification at a vent system off Panarea (Aeolian Islands, Italy). Biologia Marina Mediterranea, 26 (1), 216 - 219." type="journal article" year="2019">
Auriemma 
<emphasis box="[1264,1321,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). Its local distribution in the area and its relationship with 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[749,892,475,501]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aeoliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[749,892,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">A. aeoliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[899,989,475,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[899,989,475,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are discussed below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
